  "TYPICAL PEDON": {
    "section": "Typical Pedon",
    "content": "Typical Pedon:\nMilehigh sandy loam in urban, park. (Colors are for dry soil unless otherwise noted.)\n^A--0 to 4 centimeters; very dark grayish brown (10YR 3/2); sandy loam, black (7.5YR 2.5/1) moist; weak fine granular structure; soft, very friable, non-sticky, non-plastic; many very fine and common fine roots throughout; noneffervescent; neutral (pH 7.0); abrupt smooth boundary.\n^C--4 to 15 centimeters; brown (10YR 4/3) sandy loam, very dark grayish brown (10YR 3/2) moist; massive; slightly hard, friable, slightly sticky, non-plastic; few very fine and very few fine roots throughout; 4 percent rounded gravel; noneffervescent; neutral (pH 7.2); clear smooth boundary.\n^Cu1--15 to 31 centimeters; brown (10YR 4/3) gravelly artifactual sandy loam, very dark grayish brown (10YR 3/2) moist; massive; slightly hard, friable, non-sticky, non-plastic; very few fine roots; 10 percent subangular gravel, 10 percent gravel-sized artifacts of asphalt; noneffervescent; neutral (pH 7.2); clear smooth boundary.\n^Cu2--31 to 57 centimeters; brown (10YR 4/3), sandy loam, very dark grayish brown (10YR 3/2) moist; massive; slightly hard, friable, non-sticky, non-plastic; few fine roots throughout; 5 percent subangular gravel, 5 percent gravel-sized artifacts of asphalt; noneffervescent; neutral (pH 7.2); clear smooth boundary.\n^C'1--57 to 76 centimeters; brown (10YR 4/3), sandy loam, dark brown (10YR 3/3) moist; massive; slightly hard, friable, non-sticky, non-plastic; 2 percent subangular and subrounded fine gravel; noneffervescent; neutral (pH 7.2); gradual smooth boundary.\n^C'2--76 to 112 centimeters; yellowish brown (10YR 5/4), sandy loam, brown (10YR 4/3) moist; massive; slightly hard, friable, non-sticky, non-plastic; 2 percent subangular and subrounded gravel, noneffervescent; neutral (pH 7.2); clear smooth boundary.\n2C--112 to 200 centimeters; yellowish brown (10YR5/6), loamy sand, dark yellowish brown (10YR 4/4) moist; single grain; loose, non-sticky, non-plastic; noneffervescent; slightly alkaline (pH 7.4).\nType Location:\nDenver County, CO\nUSGS Quadrangle: Commerce City, Colorado\nLatitude: 39.7894333\nLongitude: -104.9495583\nDatum: WGS84\nCoordinates sources: Hand-held GPS\nRange in Characteristics:\nThickness of human-transported material--50 to 200 centimeters\nParticle-size control section (weighted average):\nClay content--10 to 16 percent\nSand content--60 to 75 percent\nTotal rock fragments--0 to 15 percent\n^A horizon:\nHue--7.5YR or 10YR\nValue--3 or 4 dry; 1 to 3 moist\nChroma--3 or 4 dry; 2 or 3 moist\nTexture (less than 2 mm fraction)--Clay loam, loam, sandy loam\nClay content--20 to 30 percent\nRock fragments--0 to 10 percent gravels\nReaction--pH 6.6 to 7.8\nThickness--8 to 25 centimeters\n^C horizon(s):\nHue--10YR\nValue--4 or 5 dry; 3 or 4 moist\nChroma--3 or 4 dry or moist\nTexture (less than 2 mm fraction)--Sandy loam, loamy sand, sand\nClay content--8 to 15 percent\nRock fragments--0 to 15 percent gravel\nReaction--pH 6.6 to 7.8\nThickness--8 to 40 centimeters\n^Cu horizon(s)\nHue-7.5YR or 10YR\nValue--3 to 6 dry; 1 to 3 moist\nChroma--3 to 5 dry; 2 or 3 moist\nTexture (less than 2 mm fraction)-- sandy clay loam, sandy loam\nClay content--8 to 27 percent\nRock fragments--3 to 20 percent gravel\nArtifacts--1 to 10 percent\nCalcium carbonate equivalent--1 to 5 percent\nReaction--pH 7.2 to 7.6\nThickness-15 to 35 centimeters\nC' horizon(s) (when present):\nHue--2.5Y or 10YR\nValue--6 dry; 3 to 5 moist\nChroma--4 dry; 3 or 4 moist\nTexture (less than 2 mm fraction)--sandy loam, fine sandy loam\nClay content--5 to 15 percent\nRock fragments--0 to 5 percent gravel\nReaction--pH 7.2 to 7.6\nThickness--15 to 45 centimeters\n2Bwb and/or 2BCb horizon(s) (when present):\nHue--2.5Y or 10YR\nValue--4 or 5 dry; 3 or 4 moist\nChroma--4 dry; 3 to 5 moist\nTexture (less than 2 mm fraction)--sandy clay loam, sandy loam\nClay content--2 to 25 percent\nRock fragments--0 to 5 percent gravel\nReaction--pH 7.2 to 7.6\nThickness--25 to 45 centimeters\n2C horizon(s) (when present):\nHue--10YR\nValue--3 to 5 dry or moist\nChroma--4 or 5 dry; 3 to 5 moist\nTexture (less than 2 mm fraction)--Sandy loam, loamy sand, coarse sand\nClay content--3 to 8 percent\nRock fragments--0 to 30 percent gravel\nCalcium carbonate equivalent--0 to 5 percent\nReaction--pH 7.4 to 87.8\nThickness--20 to 75 centimeters\nCompeting Series:\nThere are no competing series currently.\nGeographic Settings:\nParent material-- Thick to very thick coarse-loamy human-transported material over alluvium derived from mixed lithologies\nLandform-- Human-transported fill on Holocene and Pleistocene stream terraces\nSlope ranges--0 to 3 percent\nMean annual air temperature--10.0 to 12.0 degrees C (50.0 to 53.6 degrees F)\nMean annual precipitation range--356 to 432 millimeters (14.0 to 17.0 inches)\nFrost-free period--135 to 165 days\nElevation--1,565 to 1,690 meters (~5,135 to 5,545 feet)\nClimate--continental, temperate, semi-arid; very cold and snowy winters; cool, moist springs, hot summers, with North American monsoon precipitation from July through August.\nGeographically Associated Soils:\nRosegully soils are found on similar landscape positions but has a fine-loamy particle size control section.\nDrainage and Saturated Hydraulic Conductivity:\nDrainage class: Well and moderately well drained\nSaturated hydraulic conductivity: Moderately high (1.0 to 10 mm/sec)\nUse and Vegetation:\nMost areas are primarily used for urban development. The potential native vegetation is western sandcherry, leadplant, sand bluestem, and prairie sandreed.\nDistribution and Extent:\nHolocene and Pleistocene-aged stream terraces along the South Platte River; small extent in north-central Colorado; MLRA 67B.\nSoil Survey Region (SSR) Responsible:\nBozeman, Montana\nSeries Proposed:\nDenver County, CO 2025. Milehigh series is a coined name based on Denver's mile-high altitude.\nRemarks:\nTypical Pedon Taxonomic Features:\nOchric epipedon--0 to 4 centimeters (^A horizon)\nHuman-transported materials--0 to 112 centimeters (^A, ^C, ^Cu, C' horizons)\nArtifacts--15 to 57 centimeters (^Cu horizons)\nLithologic discontinuity--112 centimeters\nParticle-size control section-25 to 100 centimeters\nTaxonomic version: Keys to Soil Taxonomy, 13th edition, (2022)"
  },
